= <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span> merges with the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>

The electoral decline of the bourgeois right, the significant shift of the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span> toward the right, and their shared fear of the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> and <span style="color: #c00000;">socialists</span> have compelled the two parties to unite. The <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>, as the larger party, will absorb the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span>, making key concessions to facilitate the merger.

Internal reactions within the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span> are mixed. The Stresemannites and left wing vehemently oppose the merger, while the right-industrial faction supports it as a necessary step. Within the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>, opposition comes from its <span style="color: #385A38;">agrarian</span> and <span style="color: #6D5298;">Christian Socialist</span> factions, who resist unification with the industrial-capitalist <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span>. Additionally, the partyâ€™s old guard, led by Westarp, remains skeptical due to major differences on the "national questions".

